explanation:
toxdigitvalue: The target function calls this helper to interpret hex digits; its implementation (returned ranges, side effects) determines whether branches that test for negative values are ever reachable — needed to decide if those branches are dead code.

MHD_str_pct_decode_lenient_n_: Used in the MHD_FAVOR_SMALL_CODE branch; its presence/behaviour is required to determine whether the small-code path is used and whether the #ifdef branch in the target function is actually compiled or effectively dead in the project.

strlen: Called in the small-code branch. Knowledge of whether the project build uses the small branch (see MHD_FAVOR_SMALL_CODE) and how strlen is resolved (library vs replacement) is needed to decide if that branch is live.

MHD_FAVOR_SMALL_CODE (preprocessor macro): This compile-time macro controls which implementation of the function is compiled. Determining whether either branch is dead requires the build configuration for this macro.

unescape_wrapper: One of the recorded callers of the target function. To decide whether the function (or parts of it) is dead, callers must be examined to see if they ever invoke the target in the actual project paths.

MHD_http_unescape: Another recorded caller (used from URL/post processing). Its code and the conditions under which it calls the target are needed to determine if the function is reachable at runtime (used vs dead).

MHD_str_pct_decode_in_place_strict_: Included because unescape_wrapper selects between strict/lenient decode functions; understanding that selection logic is necessary to know whether the lenient version is ever invoked (and thus whether it is dead).
